Defines how sub-criteria relate to their parent criterion.
Additional Information: Examples:
1) Inheritance: in eProcurement for example, the Exclusion and Selection Criteria established in the Directives are "parents" of possible
2) Dimensions: In different business domains criteria of first order are used to group sub-criteria of second order (break-down); e.g. different domains that measure different dimensions are: - Procurement: Price, Cost, Quality - Software Product: Price, User-friendliness, Easy installation, Maintenance Assurance, etc. - Military staff selection: Aptitudes, Motivation, Personality, Physical Condition, etc.

A condition that needs to be answered for evaluation purposes.
Additional Information: 1) A criterion without properties has an informative value, e.g. it describes what it is expected form a responder. 2) A criterion can be refined through the specification of sequences of properties of type "information requirement" or "constraints". 3) Properties can be grouped in sub-criteria.

A reference to a record used to prove the veracity of a criterion.
Additional Information:
e.g. an official certificate issued by a base registry.
The CCEV Evidence reuses the UBL Document Reference. For information about UBL see http://docs.oasis-open.org/ubl/UBL-2.2.html.

Specific information needed to measure a criterion.
Additional Information:
Properties can be 1) either "information requirements", i.e. "questions" that need to be answered by a responder; 2) "constraints", i.e. limitations applied to the information requirement or to the criterion; or 3) sequences of both information requirements and constraints.
